Theresa May (right) speaks to mourners after the funeral of Lyra McKee outside St Anne's Cathedral. The popular journalist (29) was shot by a New IRA gunman in Creggan, Londonderry. Irish Taoiseach Leo Varadkar and British Prime Minister Theresa May, as well as other political leaders in attendance. Behind May and to our left is the Irish Foreign Minister, Simon Coveney. Behind May and to our far right is the Irish Taoiseach, Leo Varadkar. Directly to the left of May from our view is a security officer operating a Pressel switch (visible between thumb and forefinger). Security is always tight for British political figures in Northern Ireland. Belfast. Northern Ireland. GB. 2019.

October 1, 2019 is China's 70th National Day. Most of the "pro-China celebrations" in Hong Kong have been low-key and indoors. Out on the streets are protests in six districts on Hong Kong Island and in Kowloon. Tens of thousands of protesters dressed in black march on the streets voicing their 'Five Big Demands.' Police answer with rounds and rounds of tear gas and over a hundred protesters are arrested by midnight. Hong Kong. China. October 1, 2019.

St. Stephen's Cathedral (more commonly known by its German title, Stephansdom) is the mother church of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Vienna and the seat of the Archbishop of Vienna. The current Romanesque and Gothic form of the cathedral in the Stephansplatz, was largely initiated by Duke Rudolf IV (1339–1365) and stands on the ruins of two earlier churches. The most important religious building in Vienna, St. Stephen's Cathedral has borne witness to many important events in Habsburg and Austrian history and has, with its multi-coloured tile roof, become one of the city's most recognizable symbols.  Here, extraordinarily, a stylish woman sets her phone and selfie stick to take a selfie inside the cathedral. Vienna. Austria. 2019

Do you have a photography project you’ve been working on for years or are you about to embark on one? If so, this free workshop could be for you!
.
Join Magnum photographer @moisessaman and @time magazine’s special projects editor-at-large, @paulmoakley, for a free weekend workshop in partnership with @manacontemporary in New York on February 7-9, 2020 to explore the production, editing and publishing of long-term multimedia projects.
.
Saman and Moakley will discuss their creative relationship and how it has evolved over the years, from photographer and editor to producer and director. They will discuss the challenges of expanding from stills to video and offer advice on how to film and interview, tips for editing dialogue, creating transitions for films and building your production team.
.
For more information about this workshop and to apply, please visit magnumphotos.com/events.
.

Christmas down under can often seem uncanny, with a traditional mid-winter festivity being celebrated in the heat of the Australian summer.
.
In his family album series The Christmas Tree Bucket', Magnum photographer Trent Parke (@chillioctopus) plays on this inherent irony. Rejecting the tropes of Christmas revelry and instead amplifying the pervading sense of empty festive commercialism, Parkes hones in on the smaller details; the sun-crisp barbeques; screaming, fighting toddlers; a burning gingerbread house; the inertia of re-reading of the television guide; and the hanging, later decapitated, Santa Claus piñata. All nausea-inducing tokens of Christmas absurdism, which eventually culminate in the photographer himself vomiting into the infamous Christmas tree bucket.
.
Today on Mangum, Parke gives us a first-hand, darkly surreal account of the inspiration behind the series. Link in bio.
.

"Despite the private environment of his Paris flat in which they were taken, Beckett’s averted gaze and his stooped posture mirror the life-long uneasiness at his image or voice being forever fixed by the recording media."
.
A man who shunned the limelight, Samuel Beckett's image became well known nonetheless, as did his often darkly pessimistic writings and plays that dwell on human nature, and life’s absurdities. .
To mark the 30th anniversary of Beckett's death, scholars Mark Nixon and Galina Kiryushina reflect on a selection of rare portraits of the author and playwright and what these images reveal. Link in bio.
.
